---
import CaseStudy from '@/layouts/CaseStudy.astro';

// NOTE: No README for this one — copy is inferred from the resume line
// ("Website selling figurines and sculptures applying: Astro, TSX, and Stripe").
// Replace the specifics (who it's for, catalogue size, fulfilment details) with
// the real ones, and add a live URL to `meta` if it's deployed.
---

<CaseStudy
	title="Mango Nana — case study"
	description="A storefront for handmade figurines and sculptures, built on Astro with a TSX cart and Stripe Checkout."
	eyebrow="Case study — 2025"
	heading="Mango Nana"
	lede="A shop for handmade figurines, where every piece is one of one — which turns out to be the constraint the whole build is organised around."
	meta={[
		{ label: 'Stack', value: 'Astro · TSX islands · Stripe' },
		{ label: 'Type', value: 'E-commerce storefront' },
		{ label: 'Source', value: 'github.com/arenvista/mangonana', href: 'https://github.com/arenvista/mangonana' }
	]}
>
	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The problem</h2>
		<p>
			Off-the-shelf storefronts assume inventory: many identical units of a SKU, restocked on
			a schedule. Handmade sculpture is the opposite — each piece exists once, sells once, and
			is never made again. The listing isn't a product page so much as a photograph with a
			price on it.
		</p>
		<p>
			So the build had to be fast and mostly static, because the catalogue is images, while
			still handling real money and a stock count that only ever goes to zero.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The approach</h2>
		<p>
			Astro was the right shape for this. The catalogue is prerendered to static HTML, so
			browsing ships almost no JavaScript and the photography loads immediately on a phone.
			Only the pieces that genuinely need state — the cart and the checkout handoff — are TSX
			islands that hydrate on demand.
		</p>
		<p>
			Payment is handed to Stripe Checkout rather than rebuilt in-house. Card details never
			touch the site, which removes an entire category of problem that a small shop has no
			business owning.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>Details worth keeping</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>
				Sold pieces stay published rather than 404ing — the archive is part of the pitch for
				the next commission.
			</li>
			<li>
				Photography is the interface, so images are responsive and dimensioned up front to
				keep layout from shifting as they arrive.
			</li>
			<li>
				Cart state survives a reload, because deciding on a one-of-one piece takes more than
				one session.
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What I took away</h2>
		<p>
			Most of the work in a small storefront isn't the transaction — it's everything around a
			single irreversible moment. Getting an item out of stock the instant it sells, and
			making that legible to whoever was looking at it a second ago, mattered more than any
			feature on the roadmap.
		</p>
	</section>
</CaseStudy>
